    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy-900 mb-4">What is Business Capital?</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
      Business capital is the money your company uses to operate and grow. Working capital covers daily expenses like wages, rent, utilities, and inventory. Fixed capital goes into long-term assets like machinery, vehicles, and equipment.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
      For SMEs in Malaysia, the challenge isn't just finding capital—it's finding the <strong>right kind</strong> of capital. A loan that drains your cash flow with high monthly payments doesn't help. Financing that preserves working capital while acquiring revenue-generating equipment does.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy-900 mb-4">The Capital Trap: How Traditional Loans Drain SMEs</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
      Here's a scenario we see constantly. A construction company needs an excavator. Price: RM300,000. The bank approves the loan but requires 30% down payment. That's RM90,000 upfront.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
      That RM90,000 comes from somewhere—usually from the business's working capital. Now the company has the excavator but depleted cash reserves. When the next month's bills arrive—payroll, material costs, supplier payments—there's not enough cash. The business is asset-rich but cash-poor.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6">
      This is the capital trap. You acquire equipment to grow, but the cost of acquiring it hampers growth. The solution is financing that minimizes upfront cash outlay while spreading costs over manageable terms.
    </p>

