    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy-900 mb-4">Types of Business Capital Loans in Malaysia</h2>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-navy-800 mb-3 mt-6">Equipment Financing</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
      Equipment financing uses the machinery or vehicle you're purchasing as security. This is ideal for SMEs because the loan is backed by a productive asset—not by your cash flow alone.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
      <strong>Equipment we finance:</strong>
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-gray-700 mb-4 space-y-1">
      <li>Excavators, bulldozers, backhoes (construction)</li>
      <li>Lorries, trucks, prime movers (logistics)</li>
      <li>Forklifts, reach trucks, pallet jacks (warehousing)</li>
      <li>CNC machines, lathes, presses (manufacturing)</li>
      <li>Commercial kitchen equipment (F&B)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-navy-800 mb-3 mt-6">Hire Purchase</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
      Hire purchase is Malaysia's most common business financing structure. You make fixed monthly payments over a set term (3-5 years typically). At the end of the term, you own the equipment outright.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
      <strong>Key advantage:</strong> You can claim capital allowance on the equipment for tax purposes. Interest payments are also tax-deductible business expenses.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-navy-800 mb-3 mt-6">Operating Lease</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
      Operating lease is like long-term rental. You make monthly payments for equipment use, but don't own it at term end. This works well for equipment that becomes obsolete quickly or is needed only for specific projects.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
      <strong>Key advantage:</strong> Lease payments are fully tax-deductible operating expenses. No depreciation calculations required.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy-900 mb-4">Why 0% Down Payment Matters for SME Capital</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
      The difference between 0% down and 30% down isn't just RM90,000 on a RM300,000 excavator. It's what that RM90,000 represents for a growing SME.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
      RM90,000 could mean:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-5 text-gray-700 mb-6 space-y-2">
      <li>2 months of payroll for 10 employees</li>
      <li>Initial material purchase for a RM500,000 contract</li>
      <li>Down payment on a second piece of equipment</li>
      <li>Buffer for 3-4 months of operations</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-yellow-50 border border-yellow-200 p-6 rounded-lg my-8">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-yellow-900 mb-3">The Opportunity Cost of Down Payments</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
        When you pay RM90,000 upfront, that capital is gone from your business. It can't earn revenue. It can't cover unexpected expenses. It's trapped in the equipment.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
        With 0% down payment financing, that same RM90,000 stays in your business. It works. It generates returns. And the equipment still gets acquired—just financed instead of purchased outright.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-700">
        Over 5 years, the slightly higher monthly payment (RM130-200 difference on RM300,000 equipment) is often offset by having RM90,000 working capital available from day one.
      </p>
    </div>

